{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-05230/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-05230"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:52:30"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["extreme close-up"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman wears a blank stare."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-05230","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-05230"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1/7fc61312-2724-488c-8b1f-f55f6f392f09","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:23:04.135Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Alma’s background as a Jewish immigrant is part of what triggers her discomfort in this scene, along with her distaste for Barbara Rose’s engagement to Rubio and how Reynolds’s dress is being used as a prop (Bell, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW144026024 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.bfi.org.uk/sight-and-sound/features/paul-thomas-anderson-phantom-thread-1950s-london-haute-couture-gothic-romance-daniel-day-lewis-vicky-krieps\"><u>Paul Thomas Anderson on Phantom Thread</u></a>”). PTA commented on this excised backstory (Xixas TV, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW144026024 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f3It380DGqk\"><u>PHANTOM THREAD - AUDIO - Paul Thomas Anderson in conversation with Alan Parker</u></a>”).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:452.3125000000011,132.53685897435912,772.0753205128206,812.7724358974359"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1/a5cc4ea7-66fa-4bc8-8e7d-4a91a2c9525b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:23:42.404Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>On the subject of Porfirio’s sale of visas to Jewish refugees, C. David Haymann writes, “As Rubi’s brother, César put it: ‘He got rich selling visas to the Jews, but didn’t everyone?’ The price of a lifesaving visa ranged from $300 to $3,000, depending on supply and demand. Rubirosa purportedly sold them by the hundreds. Although he never actually denied the charge, he preferred to point out that he too was a victim of the Nazis: ‘I&nbsp;was twice arrested by the Gestapo, and twice incarcerated in prison camps, once in France, once in Germany.’ He neglected to explain that what he called ‘prison camps’ were in fact diplomatic detention centers. He was housed in luxury quarters and spent his days playing polo with high-ranking German brass” (Haymann, <em>Poor Little Rich Girl</em>, 287).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05230/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:28.1298076923089,38.29807692307725,311.81089743589735,253.3894230769231"}}}]}]}]}